@Lior Goldstein Your not far off. Yes if we start our own MGU and take as much risk as possible they will be making much less money. However the approach is that we are moving the book of business regardless so either they can keep 5-7% of premium for the fronting carrier fee or they lose everything.



Additionally as a standard rule these large carriers don't hold all the risk. They cede part of the risk to other reinsurers for various reasons (Smooth volatility, Protect against catastrophic losses, Manage capital requirements, Stabilize earnings for investors and regulators) so they are not keeping all the premiums now anyway. - When it comes to ancillary risk they hold more risk than medical but nonetheless reinsurance is a basic part of all carriers structure.



So in short they will be loosing money as we start our own MGU but not as much as you might think since they have reinsurance right now. So in theory they should be incentivized not to loose everything. (and we will be bringing them 5-7% of our D&V premiums)

@Lior Goldstein Aharon sent Larry an email but I wanted to clarify where we are at. Basically the math works out favorable for the employee at the end if the $150 value of the CPT code can be deducted from income as a medical expense.

What they want to say is that the 150 value is prepaid from the premiums. They liken it to an HMO structure (I'm not going to get into the details of that here cuz its a little complicated) but the easier analogy is like a DPC (direct primary care) which is like a membership fee of $25 a month to be able to go to the DR. at any time. In theory you are prepaying the value of the DR. care in premium (its not a perfect analogy because DPC isn't insurance - rather its like a membership fee which is why they liken it to an HMO which is insurance working in a similar way) - The problem with this is that even if its true that you can look at this like it is being prepaid from the premiums, since we are working with a section 125 plan that premium money is considered the employers and not the employees so the employee has never paid for the cost of care regardless.
Not sure how they are going to get around this. We will see what Larry says.

